fields.physical_description:
[Leather piece] Fragment of the embossed gilt leather panel, belonging to the hanging of the panelled room (La Tournerie, France). The embossed pattern consists of some leaves, a berry, part of a flower, and the wing of a bird. Painted in various colours on a gilded surface with a slightly dotted pattern.

[Leather piece] Fragment of the embossed gilt leather panel, belonging to the hanging of the panelled room (La Tournerie, France). The embossed pattern consists of foliage and flowers, a bird and a dragonfly. Painted in various colours on a gilded surface with a slightly dotted pattern. This is a fragment of the additional panels which have been produced in 1907 by G. J. Muckle, the Cottage, Pope Road, Abbots Langley, Hertfordshire.

fields.title: La Tournerie
fields.materials_techniques: Panelling of oak, painted in oil colours and oil gilded, the overmantel panel set with an oil painting of the 'Adoration of the Magi', other panels set with gilt leather (replacements after acquisition); the floor in walnut
fields.bibliography: French Renaissance Interiors. The Cabinet Maker and Complete House Furnisher. 10 December 1910, vol. XLVII, no. 585, pp. 301-3. Discusses the room as the inspiration for the alterations at Romano's Restaurant in the Strand, the interior of which is also illustrated. Fleury, Gabriel. La Chambre de Henri IV au Château de la Tournerie, reprinted from Revue historique et archéologique du Maine. vol. XLVIII. Mamers: G. Fleury et A Dangin, 1900. Pesche, J.R. Dictionnaire topographique, historique et statistique de la Sarthe, suivi d'une biographie et d'une bibliographie. Le Mans: Monnoyer and Paris: Bachelier Libraire, 1829, 6 vols., vol. 2, pp. 653-654. The brief reference to the room in this publication suggests quite clearly that it was, in 1829, in the left-hand pavilion and not in the house itself: 'Le château de la Tournerie, flanqué de deux pavillons carrés, précédé d'une cour enceinte par deux autres pavillons semblables, joints par un mur d'appui surmonté d'une balustrade en pierre, le tout entouré d'un fossé sur lequel est un pont en pierre qui a du remplacer un pont-levis, n'a rien d'intéressant dans son intérieur qu'un grand escalier en pierre, et les tuyaux qui conduisaient les eaux d'une fontaine dans les appartemens. Mais ce qui le rend intéressant, c'est la chambre où coucha le bon roi, située dans le pavillon à gauche, qu'on s'appelle la chambre de Herté, restée telle qui'il l'occupa avec ses boiseries dorées, sa tapisserie en cuir doré, son alcove avec un lit à quenouilles, à ciel et rideaux en drap bleu de ciel, brodé en soie, les peintures du ciel de lit brodées en compartimens absolument comme un dais d'église....' [The Chateau de la Tournerie, flanked by two square pavilions, fronted by an enclosed courtyard with two further, similar pavilions joined by a low wall surmounted by a balustrade, in stone, the whole surrounded by a moat over which there is a stone bridge which must have replaced a drawbridge, has nothing of interest in its interior except a grand stone staircase and the water pipes which led water to a fountain in the appartments. But what makes it interesting is the bedchamber of the good king, situated in the left-hand pavilion, which is called the chamber of Herté, which remains the same as when he occupied it, with it gilded wall panelling, its hangings in gilded leather, its alcove with a four-posted bed with tester and curtains in blue woollen cloth embroidered with silk, the designs of the tester embroidered in panels, like the canopy [baldichino] of a church.] John W. fields.history_note:
[Leather piece] The house 'la Tournerie', near Alencon, was in the years 1682-1694 in the possession of Alexander Sevin who redecorated it. In the report of T. Armstrong, dd. 29/11/1902, on the watercolour drawings of this room in the possession of architect Mons. Louis Parent, is the following passage on the gilt leather panels: 'On one of the walls at right angle of the fireplace is a large panel filled with stamped and coloured leather of a pretty design, but this leather, I am told, is in a very decayed state.' The description in French on this room contains the following passage: 'Aux murs pendent des lambeaux de ces riches tentures en cuir dore on, comme on dirait plus generalement en or basane, si recherchees autrefois pour la decoration des palais. A dont la dorure, la peinture, l'impression en relief eclairaient et rehaussaient le fond brun sombre d'arabesques et de grands ramages a fleurons dans le gout des etoffes de damas or des Indes.' The report by J. G. Jackson on his visit to the castle 'La Tournerie', 23/03/1903, is even less positive: 'The whole is in a very dilapidated state. A good deal of the wainscoting has started from the walls and the beams of the ceiling, and much of the painting has been wilfully defaced. Some of the panels were filled with painted and embossed leather, of which remains still hang in their places. ... I should not recommend any restoration of the painted decoration, but the Spanish leather panels might be made good and completed ....'. 

RPT 12689/1905 contains information about the new leather panels that have been made. 14/08/1905: An estimate of the costs of £60 to produce about 40 leather panels by G. J. Muckle, the Cottage, Pope Road, Abbots Langley, Hertfordshire. 20/12/1905: The sizes of the panels to be made. 
19/02/1906: Recommendation of A. B. Skinner to use the skills of Mr. Muckle to have these leather panels made: 'Mr. Muckle was in the Schools here and is now working at leather decoration for the trade, notably Messrs. Morant. On fact, I do not know of anyone who can execute such work in so extensive a scale. Any decoration firm will undertake the task, but it will in all probability be put out, and in most cases be sent to Paris. If we employ Mr. Muckle, we are in direct connection with the workman himself, which is a great advantage, where careful attention of colours is required. I have seen Mr. Muckle's work and think it very well done.'

RP 5597/1907: bill of G. J. Muckle, Bedmond, Kings Langley, Hertfordshire, dd. 16/12/1907. 40 panels of stamped  and painted leather for the Alencon Room. 4 Pieces border ditto, and one painted centre panel, Coat of Arms (ordered). £62. Returned to the museum: '1 large panel & a small piece of border of old leather; one painted wood panel; one old centre panel Coat of Arms'.

The border with scrolling foliage and flowers is a variant of a border produced in The Netherlands in the mid 17th century. 

Northampton, Museum of Leathercraft, inventory number 1546-67/1 (one of the copied panels).

This fragment has been analysed as part of the gilt leather cataloguing project in 1996. Eloy Koldeweij, October 1996

The report by J. G. Jackson on his visit to the castle 'La Tournerie', 23/03/1903, is even less positive: 'The whole is in a very dilapidated state. A good deal of the wainscoting has started from the walls and the beams of the ceiling, and much of the painting has been wilfully defaced. Some of the panels were filled with painted and embossed leather, of which remains still hang in their places. ... I should not recommend any restoration of the painted decoration, but the Spanish leather panels might be made good and completed ....' 
RPT 12689/1905 contains information about the new leather panels that have been made.
14/08/1905: An estimate of the costs of £60 to produce about 40 leather panels by G. J. Muckle, the Cottage, Pope Road, Abbots Langley, Hertfordshire. 20/12/1905: The sizes of the panels to be made.
19/02/1906: Recommendation of A. B. Skinner to use the skills of Mr. Muckle to have these leather panels made: 'Mr. Muckle was in the Schools here and is now working at leather decoration for the trade, notably Messrs. Morant. On fact, I do not know of anyone who can execute such work in so extensive a scale. Any decoration firm will undertake the task, but it will in all probability be put out, and in most cases be sent to Paris. If we employ Mr. Muckle, we are in direct connection with the workman himself, which is a great advantage, where careful attention of colours is required. I have seen Mr. Muckle's work and think it very well done.'
RP 5597/1907: bill of G. J. Muckle, Bedmond, Kings Langley, Hertfordshire., dd. 16/12/1907.
40 panels of stamped  and painted leather for the Alencon Room. 4 Pieces border ditto, and one painted centre panel, Coat of Arms (ordered). £62.
Returned to the museum: '1 large panel & a small piece of border of old leather; one painted wood panel; one old centre panel Coat of Arms'.

The border with scrolling foliage and flowers is a variant of a border produced in The Netherlands in the mid 17th century. 

Northampton, Museum of Leathercraft, inventory number 1546-67/1 (one of the copied panels).
